name: Dictionary.Values
desc: A view of a dictionary’s values.

items.name: typealias Dictionary.Values.Element
items.desc: A type representing the sequence’s elements.

items.name: typealias Dictionary.Values.Index
items.desc: A type that represents a position in the collection.

items.name: typealias Dictionary.Values.Indices
items.desc: A type that represents the indices that are valid for subscripting the collection, in ascending order.

items.name: typealias Dictionary.Values.SubSequence
items.desc: A collection representing a contiguous subrange of this collection’s elements. The subsequence shares indices with the original collection.

items.name: var count: Int
items.desc: The number of values in the dictionary.

items.name: var debugDescription: String
items.desc: A textual representation of this instance, suitable for debugging.

items.name: var description: String
items.desc: A textual representation of this instance.

items.name: var endIndex: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index
items.desc: The collection’s “past the end” position—that is, the position one greater than the last valid subscript argument.

items.name: var first: Value?
items.desc: The first element of the collection.

items.name: var indices: DefaultIndices<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: The indices that are valid for subscripting the collection, in ascending order.

items.name: var isEmpty: Bool
items.desc: A Boolean value indicating whether the collection is empty.

items.name: var lazy: LazySequence<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: A sequence containing the same elements as this sequence, but on which some operations, such as map and filter, are implemented lazily.

items.name: var startIndex: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index
items.desc: The position of the first element in a nonempty collection.

items.name: var underestimatedCount: Int
items.desc: A value less than or equal to the number of elements in the collection.

items.name: func allSatisfy((Value) -> Bool) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether every element of a sequence satisfies a given predicate.

items.name: func compactMap<ElementOfResult>((Value) -> ElementOfResult?) -> [ElementOfResult]
items.desc: Returns an array containing the non-nil results of calling the given transformation with each element of this sequence.

items.name: func contains(Value) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the sequence contains the given element.

items.name: func contains(where: (Value) -> Bool) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the sequence contains an element that satisfies the given predicate.

items.name: func distance(from: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, to: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Int
items.desc: Returns the distance between two indices.

items.name: func drop(while: (Value) -> Bool) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence by skipping elements while predicate returns true and returning the remaining elements.

items.name: func dropFirst(Int) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence containing all but the given number of initial elements.

items.name: func dropLast(Int) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence containing all but the specified number of final elements.

items.name: func elementsEqual<OtherSequence>(OtherSequence) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether this sequence and another sequence contain the same elements in the same order.

items.name: func elementsEqual<OtherSequence>(OtherSequence, by: (Value, OtherSequence.Element) -> Bool) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether this sequence and another sequence contain equivalent elements in the same order, using the given predicate as the equivalence test.

items.name: func enumerated() -> EnumeratedSequence<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a sequence of pairs (n, x), where n represents a consecutive integer starting at zero and x represents an element of the sequence.

items.name: func filter((Value) -> Bool) -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns an array containing, in order, the elements of the sequence that satisfy the given predicate.

items.name: func first(where: (Value) -> Bool) -> Value?
items.desc: Returns the first element of the sequence that satisfies the given predicate.

items.name: func firstIndex(of: Value) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index?
items.desc: Returns the first index where the specified value appears in the collection.

items.name: func firstIndex(where: (Value) -> Bool) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index?
items.desc: Returns the first index in which an element of the collection satisfies the given predicate.

items.name: func flatMap<SegmentOfResult>((Value) -> SegmentOfResult) -> [SegmentOfResult.Element]
items.desc: Returns an array containing the concatenated results of calling the given transformation with each element of this sequence.

items.name: func forEach((Value) -> Void)
items.desc: Calls the given closure on each element in the sequence in the same order as a for-in loop.

items.name: func formIndex(inout Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, offsetBy: Int)
items.desc: Offsets the given index by the specified distance.

items.name: func formIndex(inout Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, offsetBy: Int, limitedBy: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Bool
items.desc: Offsets the given index by the specified distance, or so that it equals the given limiting index.

items.name: func formIndex(after: inout Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index)
items.desc: Replaces the given index with its successor.

items.name: func index(Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, offsetBy: Int) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index
items.desc: Returns an index that is the specified distance from the given index.

items.name: func index(Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, offsetBy: Int, limitedBy: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index?
items.desc: Returns an index that is the specified distance from the given index, unless that distance is beyond a given limiting index.

items.name: func index(after: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index
items.desc: Returns the position immediately after the given index.

items.name: func joined() -> FlattenSequence<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>

items.name: func joined<Separator>(separator: Separator) -> JoinedSequence<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns the concatenated elements of this sequence of sequences, inserting the given separator between each element.

items.name: func lexicographicallyPrecedes<OtherSequence>(OtherSequence) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the sequence precedes another sequence in a lexicographical (dictionary) ordering, using the less-than operator (<) to compare elements.

items.name: func lexicographicallyPrecedes<OtherSequence>(OtherSequence, by: (Value, Value) -> Bool) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the sequence precedes another sequence in a lexicographical (dictionary) ordering, using the given predicate to compare elements.

items.name: func makeIterator() -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values.Iterator
items.desc: Returns an iterator over the elements of the collection.

items.name: func map<T>((Value) -> T) -> [T]
items.desc: Returns an array containing the results of mapping the given closure over the sequence’s elements.

items.name: func max() -> Value?
items.desc: Returns the maximum element in the sequence.

items.name: func max(by: (Value, Value) -> Bool) -> Value?
items.desc: Returns the maximum element in the sequence, using the given predicate as the comparison between elements.

items.name: func min() -> Value?
items.desc: Returns the minimum element in the sequence.

items.name: func min(by: (Value, Value) -> Bool) -> Value?
items.desc: Returns the minimum element in the sequence, using the given predicate as the comparison between elements.

items.name: func partition(by: (Value) -> Bool) -> Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index
items.desc: Reorders the elements of the collection such that all the elements that match the given predicate are after all the elements that don’t match.

items.name: func prefix(Int) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence, up to the specified maximum length, containing the initial elements of the collection.

items.name: func prefix(through: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence from the start of the collection through the specified position.

items.name: func prefix(upTo: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence from the start of the collection up to, but not including, the specified position.

items.name: func prefix(while: (Value) -> Bool) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence containing the initial elements until predicate returns false and skipping the remaining elements.

items.name: func randomElement() -> Value?
items.desc: Returns a random element of the collection.

items.name: func randomElement<T>(using: inout T) -> Value?
items.desc: Returns a random element of the collection, using the given generator as a source for randomness.

items.name: func reduce<Result>(Result, (Result, Value) -> Result) -> Result
items.desc: Returns the result of combining the elements of the sequence using the given closure.

items.name: func reduce<Result>(into: Result, (inout Result, Value) -> ()) -> Result
items.desc: Returns the result of combining the elements of the sequence using the given closure.

items.name: func reversed() -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns an array containing the elements of this sequence in reverse order.

items.name: func shuffled() -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns the elements of the sequence, shuffled.

items.name: func shuffled<T>(using: inout T) -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns the elements of the sequence, shuffled using the given generator as a source for randomness.

items.name: func sorted() -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns the elements of the sequence, sorted.

items.name: func sorted(by: (Value, Value) -> Bool) -> [Value]
items.desc: Returns the elements of the sequence, sorted using the given predicate as the comparison between elements.

items.name: func split(maxSplits: Int, omittingEmptySubsequences: Bool, whereSeparator: (Value) -> Bool) -> [Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>]
items.desc: Returns the longest possible subsequences of the collection, in order, that don’t contain elements satisfying the given predicate.

items.name: func split(separator: Value, maxSplits: Int, omittingEmptySubsequences: Bool) -> [Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>]
items.desc: Returns the longest possible subsequences of the collection, in order, around elements equal to the given element.

items.name: func split(separator: Value, maxSplits: Int, omittingEmptySubsequences: Bool) -> [ArraySlice<Value>]
items.desc: Returns the longest possible subsequences of the sequence, in order, around elements equal to the given element.

items.name: func starts<PossiblePrefix>(with: PossiblePrefix) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the initial elements of the sequence are the same as the elements in another sequence.

items.name: func starts<PossiblePrefix>(with: PossiblePrefix, by: (Value, PossiblePrefix.Element) -> Bool) -> Bool
items.desc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the initial elements of the sequence are equivalent to the elements in another sequence, using the given predicate as the equivalence test.

items.name: func suffix(Int) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence, up to the given maximum length, containing the final elements of the collection.

items.name: func suffix(from: Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index) -> Slice<Dictionary<Key, Value>.Values>
items.desc: Returns a subsequence from the specified position to the end of the collection.

items.name: func swapAt(Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index, Dictionary<Key, Value>.Index)
items.desc: Exchanges the values at the specified indices of the collection.

items.desc: Executes a closure on the sequence’s contiguous storage.
